<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-873-738  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 873 738.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Nov 13 1989 n274 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Flying high with OSI: airlines plan huge network. (theAeronautical Telecommunications Network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The airline industry plans to build one of the world's largestdata networks.andP;  First stages of the AeronauticalTelecommunications Network (ATN) will be based on lower-layer OpenSystems Interconnection protocols for connecting dissimilarnetworks.andP;  Planning involves upgrading existing communicationlinks that connect US and international airlines with the FAA.andO;Eventually, the ATN will provide an infrastructure and a blueprintfor interconnecting other new networks in the airline industrythrough OSI.andP;  ATN architecture could eventually includeapplications from higher layers of the OSI model such as theTransport Protocol from Layer Four and the electronic datainterchange and electronic messaging features of Layer Seven.andP;  Thedeveloper of the network is Aeronautical Radio Inc, which nowprovides the ARINC Data Network Service and a VHF-based AircraftCommunications and Reporting System.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Aeronautical Radio Inc. (planning).andO;Topic:     Airline IndustryTelecommunicationsGoals and ObjectivesOpen Systems Interconnection StandardData ManagementConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Air net of the future. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>